entries.meaning: (dated) Offspring.
examples: At the time when I am making these observations, one of his colts is the first favourite for the Derby; and it will be recollected, that a filly of his get won the Oaks in 1808.

entries.meaning: Lineage.
(sports, tennis) A difficult return or block of a shot.
(informal) Something gained; an acquisition.

verbs.description: get (third-person singular simple present gets, present participle getting, simple past got or (archaic) gat, past participle got or (United States, Canada) gotten or (Geordie) getten)

entries.meaning: (ditransitive) To obtain; to acquire.
examples: I'm going to get a computer tomorrow from the discount store.
Lance is going to get Mary a ring.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To receive.
examples: I got a computer from my parents for my birthday.
You need to get permission to leave early.
He got a severe reprimand for that.

entries.meaning: (transitive, in a perfect construction, with present-tense meaning) To have. See usage notes.
examples: I've got a concert ticket for you.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To fetch, bring, take.
examples: Can you get my bag from the living-room, please?
I need to get this to the office.

entries.meaning: (copulative) To become, or cause oneself to become.
examples: I'm getting hungry; how about you?
I'm going out to get drunk.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cause to become; to bring about.
examples: That song gets me so depressed every time I hear it.
I'll get this finished by lunchtime.
I can't get these boots off (or on).

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cause to do.
examples: Somehow she got him to agree to it.
I can't get it to work.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cause to come or go or move.
examples: I got him to his room.

entries.meaning: (intransitive, with various prepositions, such as into, over, or behind; for specific idiomatic senses see individual entries get into, get over, etc.) To adopt, assume, arrive at, or progress towards (a certain position, location, state).
examples: The actors are getting into position.
When are we going to get to London?
I'm getting into a muddle.
We got behind the wall.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cover (a certain distance) while travelling.
examples: to get a mile

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To begin (doing something or to do something).
examples: We ought to get moving or we'll be late.
After lunch we got chatting.
I'm getting to like him better now.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To take or catch (a scheduled transportation service).
examples: I normally get the 7:45 train.
I'll get the 9 a.m. [flight] to Boston.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To respond to (a telephone call, a doorbell, etc).
examples: Can you get that call, please? I'm busy.

entries.meaning: (intransitive, followed by infinitive) To be able, be permitted, or have the opportunity (to do something desirable or ironically implied to be desirable).
examples: I'm so jealous that you got to see them perform live!
The finders get to keep 80 percent of the treasure.
Great. I get to clean the toilets today.

entries.meaning: (transitive, informal) To understand. (compare get it)
examples: Yeah, I get it, it's just not funny.
I don't get what you mean by "fun". This place sucks!
I mentioned that I was feeling sad, so she mailed me a box of chocolates. She gets me.

entries.meaning: (transitive, informal) To be told; be the recipient of (a question, comparison, opinion, etc.).
examples: "You look just like Helen Mirren." / "I get that a lot."

entries.meaning: (informal) To be. Used to form the passive of verbs.
examples: He got bitten by a dog.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To become ill with or catch (a disease).
examples: I went on holiday and got malaria.

entries.meaning: (transitive, informal) To catch out, trick successfully.
examples: He keeps calling pretending to be my boss‚Äîit gets me every time.

entries.meaning: (transitive, informal) To perplex, stump.
examples: That question's really got me.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To find as an answer.
examples: What did you get for question four?

entries.meaning: (transitive, informal) To bring to reckoning; to catch (as a criminal); to effect retribution.
examples: The cops finally got me.
I'm gonna get him for that.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To hear completely; catch.
examples: Sorry, I didn't get that. Could you repeat it?

entries.meaning: (transitive) To getter.
examples: I put the getter into the container to get the gases.

entries.meaning: (now rare) To beget (of a father).
examples: Walter had said, dear God, Thomas, it was St fucking Felicity if I'm not mistaken, and her face was to the wall for sure the night I got you.

entries.meaning: (archaic) To learn; to commit to memory; to memorize; sometimes with out.
examples: to get a lesson;‚ÄÉ to get out one's Greek lesson

entries.meaning: (imperative, informal) Used with a personal pronoun to indicate that someone is being pretentious or grandiose.
examples: Get her with her new hairdo.

entries.meaning: (intransitive, informal, chiefly imperative) To go, to leave; to scram.
examples: I had a sneaking suspicion that it wasn't no flashlight and I wasn't too curious, just then, to find out what would happen if he did more than wave it at me, so I got. I went back about twenty feet or so and watched.

entries.meaning: (euphemistic) To kill.
examples: They‚Äôre coming to get you, Barbara.

entries.meaning: (intransitive, obsolete) To make acquisitions; to gain; to profit.
(transitive) To measure.
examples: Did you get her temperature?

entries.meaning: (Britain, regional) Synonym of git (‚Äúcontemptible person‚Äù)
examples: Although get is the original word, the derived word git is more common.

nouns.description: get (plural gets or gittim or gitten)

entries.meaning: (Judaism) A Jewish writ of divorce.
examples: In Israel, rabbinic courts can imprison men until they acquiesce and grant gets to their wives.
